26 2021-01-03 sensitivity to light, ear discomfort, vision blurred, ringing in ears I received the shot around 0730 on 12/30/2020. Went home and got ready for work. Around 12am 12/31/2... Read more
Close
I received the shot around 0730 on 12/30/2020. Went home and got ready for work. Around 12am 12/31/2020 my arm started to radiate at the injection site and was very tense. I placed a heat pack on the right harm but the pain did not dissipate. My arm continued to be in pain for the rest of the night. Around 0240 I ate dinner, had water and still had some arm pain. Around 0345 my arm started to flare up and sent pain sensations throughout my body. My right arm was increasingly discomforting, I could barely move it. The sensations spread to my legs, numbing them and my throat had felt as if it were closing up. I got up to get the attention of the nurse and was able to flag her down. She said I was pale as a ghost. My vision was very blurry, I could not hear anything because my ears had filled up and everything was muffled. My head had begun to ring and I was on the brink of fainting when a chair was given to me. My eyes had become extremely sensitive to the light, I was given water and spoken to about what had happened leading up to the event. I was greeted by the paramedics who drew my blood, placed an IV and transferred me to the Acute Care portion of the Emergency Department. My vitals were 76/49, 80/50, 90/56, 100/60 before being brought to the ER. On 1/1/2021 My thighs have been sore/tense, my knees and ankles have been stiff and just feeling sickly. On 1/2/2021 much of the same symptoms are present. The soreness in the muscles isn't as prevalent, however joints still are stiff On 1/3/2021, congestion and runny nose are still present, stiffness in ankles and now shins are prevalent.

26 2021-03-29 vision blurred, eye irritation, lacrimation increased For BOTH initial (022621) and booster (032621) of Moderna, pt had moderate/severe eye reaction. Over... Read more
Close
For BOTH initial (022621) and booster (032621) of Moderna, pt had moderate/severe eye reaction. Overnight about 3 days after first injection and 4 days after second injection. Initial injection: pt went to bed on the 3rd night after vaccine having taken no medications and noted mild eye irritation. He woke up a few hours later (~midnight) to severe eye watering and blurriness which required him to keep his eyes closed with mild sinus congestion. No difficulty breathing noted. Pt had trouble getting it to stop despite taking loratadine 10mg and rinsing eyes with water. Pt seriously considered going to ER due to risk of blindness. Pt eventually fell asleep a few hours later and woke up with very sensitive eyes (irritated, very red) that took about 36h to fully recover. Second injection: pt was on scheduled loratadine 10mg daily. Noted a similar eye irritation (this time four days after injection not three) when going to bed and took 50mg diphenhydramine (about 14h after loratadine dose). Woke up a few hours later to more minor but still debilitating eye watering with proportionally more sinus involvement. No difficulty breathing noted. Pt took an extended release pseudoephedrine, rinsed eyes with water and waited for it to resolve about an hour or two later. Pt awoke the next morning to much less sensitive eyes than first time. Note: due to first experience. From time of administration of second dose, pt was on scheduled naproxen (440mg loading dose followed by 220mg q12h), loratadine 10mg q24h, and pseudoephedrine (120mg ER q24h). Pt took these scheduled days 1-3 and at time of second eye episode was only on scheduled loratadine still. Pt also had 50mg diphenhydramine on hand in case of episode.

26 2021-04-12 vision blurred, visual impairment Patient noted on form that he had a severe reaction to peanuts which causes him to have anaphylaxis.... Read more
Close
Patient noted on form that he had a severe reaction to peanuts which causes him to have anaphylaxis. He stated that he does carry an EpiPen and any time anything with peanuts touches his mouth/lips he immediately notices his throat starting to close. He also is allergic to cats. Before administering the vaccine, the patient noted that he does not like needles and was not going to look. I administered the vaccine and the patient and I exited the vaccination room. I explained that he should sit in the waiting area for about 30 minutes due to his severe allergic reaction in the past. By the time that I walked back into the pharmacy, the patient's wife shouted "He's not breathing!". My technicians called 911 while I grabbed an EpiPen and rushed to the patient. I immediately administered a 0.3 mg dose of epinephrine and observed that the patient had passed out, was not breathing, but had a pulse. A few seconds later he regained consciousness and his breathing was erratic. I gave him water and he stated that he felt very lightheaded and dizzy. I instructed him to remain seated. He also noted that his vision was blurry and he saw a black dot. His wife was fanning him to cool him down while I tried to obtain the patient's blood pressure, but could not get a reading. The paramedics came and evaluated him thoroughly. His blood pressure, heart rate, EKG, and blood sugar were all within normal limits. They determined that the syncope was most likely due to the patient not eating during the day and not liking needles. The patient was feeling much better and declined further medical treatment, including going to the hospital. He was instructed to go home and relax.

26 2021-04-17 tunnel vision Patient received dose 1 of Moderna COVID-19 vaccine. Approximately 5-10 minutes after administration... Read more
Close
Patient received dose 1 of Moderna COVID-19 vaccine. Approximately 5-10 minutes after administration, the patient's mother alerted me that the patient was feeling faint and sweaty. I came to check on the patient. He appeared pale and diaphoretic. Patient said his vision was narrowing and he subsequently lost consciousness for approximately 10-20 seconds. I checked the patient's blood pressure and initial result was 88/64. Upon regaining consciousness, patient reported immediately feeling better. His blood pressure was still low at 94/70. He remained seated and drank some cold water and a cool compress was applied to his forehead. I questioned the patient to determine if he was experiencing any other symptoms that may indicate anaphylaxis (skin itchiness, tight throat, stomach upset) and he denied any other symptoms. I continued to monitor the patient for approximately 30 minutes. During monitoring, the patient told me he is nervous of needles, and has fainted trying to give blood in the past. After 30 minutes of monitoring, diaphoresis had resolved, color returned to patient's face, blood pressure recheck was 116/84, and patient self-reported feeling fine. He was escorted home by his mother.

Pt. received his second dose Moderna Vaccine and shortly after he stated that he felt tingling and tightness in the throat and neck with warm sensation around neck. Pt also verbalized difficulty swallowing. NP?s assisted patient and assessed Pt status. Pt remained in ER observation for further monitoring and safety precautions. Pt denied any reactions to prior vaccine (first dose Moderna). Pt given hydration and was able to drink 8oz of fluid without any difficulty. Pt remained alert and oriented x3 and coherent, his initial v/s were 117/78 pulse 72, 129/81 P 76, o2 sat 99% room air. 28 2021-04-11 lacrimation increased I received the first dose of the Moderna vaccine at 2:55pm on 4/7. An hour or two later, I started... Read more
Close
I received the first dose of the Moderna vaccine at 2:55pm on 4/7. An hour or two later, I started to get a sore throat. The sore throat was very painful by the early morning of 4/8. On 4/8 I went into a doctor to see if I had strep throat because of the level of pain and since I didn't think I could get a sore throat from the vaccine, but he said it was not strep and that it was likely just a side effect of the vaccine. On 4/8 I also had a fever topping 101.4, fatigue (I slept a lot that day), mental fog, pain at injection site, and all-around body pain. The sore throat lessened greatly by 4/9, so it clearly wasn't a strep infection and seems it was indeed a side effect of the vaccine. From 4/9 through 4/11 I had general "cold" symptoms: runny nose, phlegmy, watery eyes, redness and pain at injection site, muscle aches, elevated temperature (not fever), and general fatigue. By 4/12, these symptoms are nearly completely gone. Some of these symptoms seemed quite strange as side effects from the vaccine, but they started and perfectly paralleled the expected vaccine side-effects, which makes me think they were caused by the vaccine. I have no reason to think I had another illness at the same time as when I was experiencing these side-effects. I had had Covid-19 previously (in December 2020; I tested positive and had mild symptoms). Perhaps having had Covid-19 already provoked these strange side-effects.

31 2021-04-06 tunnel vision At approximately 9:00 PM (roughly 11.5 hours after vaccination) I became extremely light headed wit... Read more
Close
At approximately 9:00 PM (roughly 11.5 hours after vaccination) I became extremely light headed with slurred speech. I experienced tunnel vision and dizziness. My face turned white, and my lips were a blue color. I sat down immediately, which improved my condition temporarily. But, within 2 minutes I began experiencing tunnel vision and dizziness again while sitting upright. I laid down on my back and elevated my legs. My vision returned and but I remained dizzy and pale. I experienced some numbness and tingling in my extremities. My wife attached a fingertip pulse oximeter to my finger at this time (we did not have a tool to check blood pressure on hand). My blood %SpO2 read between 95 and 98% and pulse ranged from 95 to 101 bpm. I did NOT experience: difficulty breathing, swelling of the airway, nor itching. Since I was not having difficulty breathing, and my symptoms seemed to indicate low blood pressure or potentially low blood sugar I decided to wait it out and see if my symptoms worsened. While laying on the floor, I consumed a glass of milk and a few oreo cookies, hoping to counter hypoglycemia (if that's what was going on). After approximately 15 minutes my condition began to improve - I could sit up slightly with only mild dizziness and color began returning to my face. After approximately 30 minutes, I was able to stand and walk to my couch and lay down. After around an hour, I was feeling almost back to normal with only a slight dizziness and tiredness remaining. 12 hours after the adverse event (24 hours post vaccination) I feel okay, slightly lightheaded but generally fine. I intend to call a doctor and discuss if any further tests are necessary.

It's been nearly a month without much improvement.

All medical professionals opined that the moderna vaccine must have played a role given the timing. If shingles can be considered a side effect, it is one that has been intense and long-lasting.

38 2021-05-03 vision blurred On Friday, April 2nd, I received my first dose of the Moderna vaccine. Within minutes, my heart sta... Read more
Close
On Friday, April 2nd, I received my first dose of the Moderna vaccine. Within minutes, my heart started racing and I felt faint. Thereafter, my hands and face got the sensation of tingling. It felt like ice was running through my veins. My heart stopped racing approximately fifteen or so minutes after it began. The tingling sensation in my hands and face ended approximately one hour later. I also noticed a strange taste in my mouth during this same timeframe. Subsequently, I had the sensation of being dizzy and lightheaded. Importantly, I have never reacted to a vaccine in this manner. On Saturday, April 3rd, I woke up with symptoms that were to be expected. My arm was very sore and I felt a little achy. However, I continued to feel dizzy and lightheaded. That evening and for the next week or so, my heart was beating rapidly, and my blood pressure was elevated. I also had the continuous feeling of my skin crawling. My hands and feet also seemed to be experiencing tremors and twitching. On Sunday, April 4th, I woke up and noticed that my right eye seemed a little blurry as I read an article on my phone. I assumed I must have slept on my eye wrong and did not pay it much attention. I do not recall my eye being blurry for the rest of the day. The following morning on Monday, April 5th, I woke up once again feeling dizzy and lightheaded. As I walked to the restroom, I noticed that my right eye was blurry again. This time it seemed to be more pronounced. Moreover, when I closed my right eye, I could see hundreds of dots in different colors. In addition to having blurry vision, my legs felt weak and nearly buckled as I walked. I felt like I was intoxicated. Upon returning to bed, my teeth began chattering and I felt like I was freezing. I called my doctor?s office and spoke with a PA who recommended that I go to the ER. While I checked in at the ER, I could not remember my ZIP code. I felt like my brain was not running on all cylinders. Upon explaining my symptomology to the ER doctor, she recommended that I have my blood drawn and that I get an MRI to rule out a stroke. All test results came back normal. On Wednesday, April 7th, I made an appointment with an allergist. They tested me to see if I was allergic to Polyethylene Glycol (PEG) and Polysorbate 80. For the skin scratch portion of the test, neither of the substances had much of a reaction on my skin. I thought the Polysorbate 80 scratch had a little bit of redness to it, but it was negligible. When the doctor injected Polysorbate 80 under my skin with a syringe, a welt formed. I am not sure why, but PEG was not injected in the same manner. As a result of the test, the allergist confirmed that I am allergic to Polysorbate 80. He mentioned that there may be instances of cross reactivity to PEG for individuals that are allergic to Polysorbate 80. He recommended that I not get the second Moderna dose unless it was administered in a controlled setting. On Sunday April 11th, I noticed what felt like a hard vein in my abdominal fat. It felt slightly tender to the touch. I was fearful that it could be a clot. On Tuesday, April 13th, I woke up and as a I stood in the shower, my foot was painful to stand on. On top of my right foot near my ankle, I could visibly see red inflammation in a vein. I massaged the vein and the redness and pain dissipated. Being fearful that I did have blood clots, I scheduled an appointment with a PA at my doctor?s office that same day. We discussed my ongoing dizziness, lightheadedness, and me being fearful of blood clots. She had an EKG performed at the office and ordered a barrage of blood tests. Everything continued to be normal. On Sunday, April 18th, I again went to the ER, because the hard vein in my stomach became larger and more tender to the touch. When I bent over, it felt like there was a lot of pressure emanating from the hard vein down to my groin. Once again, blood was drawn and everything was normal. I also had an ultrasound performed on the area that felt like a hard vein and the doctor concluded that it was most likely swollen lymph nodes. I was diagnosed with lymphadenopathy. On Monday, April 26th, I scheduled an appointment with my primary care doctor to discuss the ongoing dizziness, lightheadedness, and pain in my stomach and groin area. He told me that he had seen other patients that were experiencing similar symptoms and that my immune system was possibly overreacting to the vaccine. He told me the symptoms should go away in time. He also ordered a new blood test to check for clots. The D-Dimer test came back normal. On Tuesday, April 27th, I experienced a painful genital herpes outbreak. I normally get one every year. I had just recovered from an infection in December of 2020. This outbreak was more intense and for the first time I had nerve pain that wrapped around my hip and down my inner thigh. As of a week later, the infection is almost gone. Today is May 4th, and I am still experiencing dizziness and lightheadedness. Some days are better than others and every time I get optimistic that my dizziness and lightheadedness is finally gone, it reappears. Being an IT consultant business owner and an attorney, I need to think clearly for my profession. The side effects from the Moderna vaccine have made it very difficult to function. I would like to get fully vaccinated, but I am fearful of getting the second shot. I do not want the vaccine to cause permanent neurological damage or worse. Finally, I am sure your organization is aware, but there are many other people experiencing the same symptoms as me.

39 2021-02-19 deafness unilateral, ringing in ears On January 1 and 2nd, approximately 10 days following administration of Moderna vaccination, I be... Read more
Close
On January 1 and 2nd, approximately 10 days following administration of Moderna vaccination, I began to experience both hearing loss and tinnitus in my right ear. The hearing loss and ringing noise in my right ear came on rather slowly, and progressed over a week's time. There was no illness otherwise, and no trauma. The ringing continued, and I sought out medical care from both Neurology and Otolaryngology. My otolaryngologist could not find any cause and speculated that it could in fact be from the vaccination. I underwent oral steroid treatment as well as a series of 3, sequential weekly steroid injections into my middle ear space, though my tympanic membrane. I also started taking oral L-Lysine at the recommendation of my neurologist as well as other herbals including oral flavonoids to help reduce tinnitus. None of the above treatments have made any improvement in my symptoms. I had my hearing rechecked every week at ENT office and the same degree of hearing loss is evident. None of which has returned to date. I have most recently just last week begun to a pursue hearing aid device at the recommendation of my ENT physician. 39 2021-06-01 visual impairment 1 week after the second dose, I was exercising in the early morning when suddenly my vision and hand... Read more
Close
1 week after the second dose, I was exercising in the early morning when suddenly my vision and hand-eye coordination were flashing, my hand appeared in a different position than where I thought it was. I tried to tell my sons to get help, but I couldn't say any words, just some repetitive mumbling. I was able to walk upstairs but couldn't speak for about 10 mins, and then everything was coming out slowly. It was about an hour before I could resume normal talking. I went to the hospital, where they gave me a CT scan, MRI, heart echo, and eventually a TEE. They said that I had a Transient Ischemic Attack, and they found a PFO in my heart that probably allowed a blood clot to travel to my brain. They also did an ultrasound of my legs when I mentioned the timing of the vaccine, to make sure there were no other clots. I am taking baby asprin and crestor, and have an heart event monitor now for 30 days. I am also scheduled for more bloodwork and a pelvic scan. They say it is likely that they will want to close my PFO, but want to see all the test results first to rule out any other possible causes.

39 2021-06-30 hearing loss, ringing in ears, ear discomfort, permanent deafness, sudden hearing loss, deafness unilateral Sudden sensorineural hearing loss in the right ear. In the evening on May 8, I suddenly experienced... Read more
Close
Sudden sensorineural hearing loss in the right ear. In the evening on May 8, I suddenly experienced a sense of fullness, partial hearing loss, and tinnitus in the right ear. On May 9, I went to an urgent care clinic and was diagnosed with eustachian tube dysfunction. I was instructed to take pseudoephedrine and a steroid nasal spray and told that it should clear up in a week or two. When my hearing did not return after a couple of weeks, I saw an ENT on May 27 and was diagnosed with conductive hearing loss and put on a course of oral steroids. I sought a second opinion and saw an audiologist on June 10, where I was diagnosed with sensorineural hearing loss. I was given a stronger course of oral steroids, followed by two intratympanic steroid injections. Neither the oral steroids nor the steroid injections have reversed any of my hearing loss, so it appears that I have permanent partial hearing loss and tinnitus in my right ear.

The night of my second shot (around 8pm PST) I experienced extreme warm sensations in both feed, almost able to feel the contours of the nerves in my feet. My toungue also felt cold later that night, and the nerves in my legs felt cold, despite my skin feeling warm. I continued feeling warm sensations across both feet in the evenings and when sleeping throughout the following 2 weeks. Beyond that I've continued to have a warm/swollen sensation in the nerves in my legs below my knees, concentrated in shins. I've had a similar sensation in my forearms. It should be noted that after my first shot (on 3/30), about a week later I started developing intermitent headaches, and then around mid april developed intermitent facial numbness and and some pain in my left jaw and around my teeth, but the proximity to my first shot wasnt as close, so didnt report that in this form.
